<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{bakari}}}} is a particle which is indicates which carries the idea of only or of "just done", ""just doing" or "about to do".
</p>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@Vta{{}} @EM{{@HI{{bakari}}}} indicates that something has just happened or has just been done. It is the
speaker's feeling that determines whether the action is recent or not.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{sakki @KJ{{daytime}}gohanwo @KJ{{eat}}beta @EM{{bakari}} desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I had lunch just a little while ago.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@Vte{{}} @EM{{@HI{{bakari}}}} indicates that something is being done, with a nuance that nothing else is being done.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{springtime^creek}}ha@KJ{{cry}}te@EM{{bakari}}ite@KJ{{what}}mo@KJ{{tale}}soutoshinai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Harue is crying and won't talk about anything.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@Vru{{}} @EM{{@HI{{bakari}}}} indicates that something is about to be done.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{kono@KT{{repo-to}}haato@KJ{{tie^argument}}wo@KJ{{write}}ku@EM{{bakari}}da.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    The only thing left to do with this report is to write a conclusion.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
In classical Japanese @EM{{@HI{{bakari}}}} expressed the speaker's conjecture and this is still seen
in <em>quantifier</em> @EM{{@HI{{bakari}}}}, which means "about".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{ten^person}}@EM{{bakari}}no@KJ{{friend^accomplished}}ga@KJ{{hand^transmit}}ttekuremashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    About 10 friends helped me.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}denai}} expresses the idea of "not also but also". In this usage it can be replaced by
<a href="grammar-dake.html">@HI{{dake}}</a> but @EM{{@HI{{bakari}}}} is slightly more emphatic.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{England^word}}@EM{{bakari}}denaku,@KT{{furansu}}@KJ{{word}}mo@KJ{{exertion^strong}}shitaindesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I want to study not only English but French too.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{bakari}}}} emphasises the singularity of the immediately preceding word.
</p>
<p>
The position of @EM{{@HI{{bakari}}}} slightly changes the meaning, so several versions of a sentence are
supplied to show the difference.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{chapter^long}}:kachou}}hakono@KJ{{time}}@KT{{uisuki-}}@EM{{bakari}}@KJ{{drink}}ndeimasune.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    The section chief is drinking nothing but whiskey these days.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{chapter^long}}:kachou}}hakono@KJ{{time}}@KT{{uisuki-}}wo@KJ{{drink}}nde@EM{{bakari}}imasune.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    The section chief is doing nothing but drinking whiskey these days.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{chapter^long}}:kachou}}hakono@KJ{{time}}@KT{{uisuki-}}@KJ{{drink}}ndeiru@EM{{bakari}}desune.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    All the section chief does these days is drink whiskey.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{bakarini}}}} emphasises a reason or a cause.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{transit^environs}}:watanabe}}sanha@KT{{sutereo}}wo@KJ{{buy}}itai@EM{{barakini}},
    @FG{{@KJ{{one^life^suspend^fate}}:isshoukenmei}}ni@KT{{arubaito}}woshiteiru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Watanbe is working like a dog at his part-time job because he wants to buy a stereo so badly.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
When @EM{{@HI{{bakari}}}} follows @HI{{ga}} or @HI{{wo}}, these particles drop. When it follows
@HI{{ni}} or @HI{{he}}, these particles may optionally drop. Other particles remain.
</p>

